<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-847-597  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 847 597.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Today's Office  August 1990 v25 n3 p28(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Electronic mail cuts through the paper bottleneck.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miller, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The rapid growth in the use of electronic mail systems can beattributed to the benefits the systems offer businesses such as areduction in paperwork, quick and efficient intra- andinter-company communications, increased productivity, and reducedcosts.andP;  Electronic mail enables employees in large organizationsto solicit and send information via distribution lists efficientlyand quickly.andP;  A reduction in paperwork provided by the systems cancut costs.andP;  Intra-company communications are usually deliveredwithin minutes, and inter-company mail within an hour.andP;  Employeeson the road can transmit and receive electronic mail on portablecomputers.andP;  The levels of electronic mail systems are: basicprograms for transmitting documents, messaging software forsending and receiving more complex documents, and electronic datainterchange programs that permit the replacement of paperinvoices, order forms, and other key business document withelectronic equivalents.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic Mail SystemsOffice AutomationCommunications SoftwareElectronic Data InterchangeOrganizational CommunicationsFile TransferTeleconferencing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>